# WSL Builds Project Context

## Documentation audiences

- **`README.md` (repo root):** End users—what the project is, how to install/configure, how to run **the builder** (`./wsl-builder.sh`), high-level build/component lists. Not maintainer walkthroughs, script wiring, or instructions aimed only at agents. Skip table “legends” or other meta lines about formatting (those belong in **CONTRIBUTING.md** or `.cursor/rules/`).
- **`CONTRIBUTING.md`:** Contributors—ShellCheck/`bash -n` lint workflow (**Linting**), how to add builds/components, metadata/dispatch (`conf.sh`, `install.sh`, `src/install-dispatch.sh`). Canonical prose for that lives in **Contributing builds / components**.
- **`test/README.md`:** Running `./test/run-tests.sh`, Docker/Bats harness, catalogs for **build-fixture** tests (`builder-tests.bats`) and **wizard** tests (`conf-wizard-tests.bats`).
- **`.cursor/rules/`:** Operational context for the assistant—invariants (e.g. supported entrypoint is **`./wsl-builder.sh`** (**the builder**); `install.sh` is not meant to be executed standalone), bash conventions, where tests live. Keep rules short; point to **`CONTRIBUTING.md`** for contributor prose and **`test/README.md`** for the testing harness.

## Project behaviour

- **Terminology:** In explanatory prose (rules, skills, informal contributor context), prefer **the builder** as shorthand for the supported root entrypoint **`./wsl-builder.sh`**. Use the literal **`./wsl-builder.sh`** in fenced command examples, lint/ShellCheck lists, `bash -n` lines, and anywhere the path must be exact.
- This repository is a simple WSL2 build system made from Bash scripts. Bash **function** names use **camelCase** (no `snake_case`).
- It is not a package manager or a framework; keep changes small, explicit, and easy to inspect.
- Builds are stacked by running **`./wsl-builder.sh`** `<build-dir> <component>[,<component>...] [additionalargs]... [--force]`.
- Each stack lives under **`builds/<name>/`**: a `conf.sh` (calls `registerBuildMetadata` in `src/build-metadata.sh`), an `install.sh` (sources `src/install-dispatch.sh` only), and optional `install_<component>.sh` files. Shared dispatch logic runs at top level in `install-dispatch.sh` when **the builder** sources `install.sh`.
- Components should install/configure one focused thing and fit the existing local patterns.
- **Systemd / boot:** When adding or reviewing a component, determine whether the install enables a **systemd** (or other) **start-on-boot** daemon. If it does and the script has no optional **`promptYesNo`** + **`systemctl disable --now`** pattern yet, **ask the user** whether they want that UX added—see **`.cursor/rules/bash-component-patterns.mdc`** (*Optional: disable start on boot*) and **`builds/ai/install_ollama.sh`**. Do not add disable prompts without agreement; many services are expected to stay enabled.
- Prefer existing helpers in `src/` over adding new mechanisms.
- Optional **large cache or artifact paths** for a component are configured in gitignored repo-root **`wsl-builds.conf`**; add commented examples to **`wsl-builds.conf.example`** when introducing new keys. Conventions: **`.cursor/rules/bash-component-patterns.mdc`** (user-configured caches vs `getFile` / `CACHE_DIR`).
- Update **`README.md`** when adding or changing **user-visible** build behaviour (new components users select, args they pass, or build directory purpose). Do **not** put implementation or agent-only notes in the root README—use **`CONTRIBUTING.md`** or rely on Cursor rules.
- After changes that materially affect **contributor workflow**, **test/lint mechanics**, **scaffolding/component patterns**, or **invariants agents rely on**, check whether **`CONTRIBUTING.md`**, **`.cursor/rules/`**, and **`.cursor/skills/`** still match reality; refresh **only where** text would mislead—skip this for trivial typo-only edits or narrowly local fixes that do not change behaviour or conventions.
- Before non-trivial answers or edits, skim `README.md` and `CONTRIBUTING.md` at the repo root, plus the relevant **`builds/<build-dir>/README.md`** if a specific build is involved.
- **[`bats-core`](https://github.com/bats-core/bats-core)** tests in **`test/docker/*.bats`** run **only inside Docker**: the test image **copies the repo at build time** (no host bind mount); use **`test/run-tests.sh`** locally (lint + image build + run). Before changing **`wsl-builder.sh`**, `src/install-dispatch.sh`, helpers, or Bats tests, skim **`test/README.md`**.
- **`User-visible wording`:** Editing exact stdout text (`printInfo` / `printWarning` / `printError`, usage lines, **`getFile`** / **`promptYesNo`** prompts, **`configure.sh`** messages) can fail Bats assertions (`[[ output =~ … ]]`, **`grep`** on **`$output`**). Before finishing those edits, **`rg`** (or **`grep`**) **`test/`** and **`builds/test-fixture/`** for distinctive substrings from the previous message—or scan **`test/docker/*.bats`** when you touched shared helpers—and update assertions or harness wording in the **same change**; run **`./test/run-tests.sh`** when **`src/`**, **`wsl-builder.sh`**, **`configure.sh`**, or test fixtures are involved.
- **User config vs harness:** Repo-root **`/wsl-builds.conf`** is gitignored and listed in **`test/docker/Dockerfile.dockerignore`** with a **root-anchored** pattern (`/wsl-builds.conf`). An unanchored `wsl-builds.conf` ignores/excludes **`test/docker/wsl-builds.conf`** as well—breaking clones and Docker `COPY`. If you touch those ignore files or rename harness config, verify the harness stays tracked and present in the image.
